Those who perform abortions in practice are rarely held accountable, but it should be noted that a section of the Penal Code of the Republic of Panama does provide the death penalty for infanticide. Despite the law, however, it is actually very rare for lost pregnancies to result in charges for either the mother or doctor, so it remains uncertain as to how truly severe penalties could be. Done in very small amounts, the abortifacient drug mifepristone can be purchased under the name Mifeprex brand in Mexico, Panama and the Republic of Trinidad and Tobago, but it is not licensed in Panama.

Interestingly, legislation related to abortion is only sometimes used in Panama, as there have been cases where pregnant women have obtained criminal punishments for illegal abortion due to consciously destroying the fetus after it had already taken hold and although the intent was to terminate the pregnancy, it maintained its life and is deemed an infanticide. Such cases are very unusual, but they have occurred.

Despite reincorporating internationally obligatory covenants disseminating information on sexual health, the Panamanian government still does not promote access to family planning and contraception for women, and it has been shown that many women have attempted to undergo illegal abortions.
